{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} [[File:TurnerMuseum02.jpg|400px|right|Museum viewed from coffee bar end]] The '''Turner Museum of Glass''' is housed in the Department of Materials Science and Engineering at the [[University of Sheffield]], in England. It is in the Hadfield Building with the entrance from Portobello Street. It contains examples from ancient Egypt and Rome but mainly from major European and American glassworkers, with a particular focus on those from the 1920s to 1950s.<ref name=TMW>[http://www.turnermuseum.group.shef.ac.uk/biography.html Museum website]</ref>
It was founded in 1943 by Professor [[W E S Turner]]<ref name=SandS>[http://www.scienceandsociety.co.uk/results.asp?image=10303200&wwwflag=2&imagepos=3 www.scienceandsociety.co.uk]</ref><ref name=biog>[http://www.turnermuseum.group.shef.ac.uk/biography.html Museum website] Biography of Turner</ref> of the University, who additionally was the senior author on many [[scientific papers|papers]] on [[glass]] technology.<ref name=SGT>[http://www.societyofglasstechnology.org.uk/cgi-bin/open.cgi?page=JSGT/JSGT-04 Society of Glass Technology] List of Papers on Glass Technology</ref> One of the exhibits is the wedding dress of his wife (Helen Nairn, married 1 July 1943<ref name=sign>according to the sign beside the exhibit</ref>) which is made of glass fibre, as are the matching shoes. This has been selected as one of the items in the [[BBC]]'s [[A History of the World in 100 Objects]].<ref name=bbc100>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/NolQSkbeRc-6HNQvhF1J_A BBC A History of the World] Glass Fibre Wedding Dress</ref>
